#795
@@yBleached Bone Hollow@@N~
@@yA depression in the dunes forms a natural hollow, and within it lies a graveyard of ancient creatures. Bleached bones of unknown creatures lie scattered across the sand in no particular pattern, each one sun-whitened to the color of chalk and brittle as dried reeds. The skulls of large beasts—some as wide as a man is tall—stare blindly at the merciless sky with empty sockets, weathered beyond any recognition of what they once were. Some bones are articulated, suggesting the creatures died where they fell. Others are scattered as if scattered by scavengers or storms. The oldest bones have begun to fuse with the sand itself, becoming part of the desert's geological record. The scale of the bones suggests creatures that would have been fearsome in life—perhaps they were driven here to die of thirst and exposure. Or perhaps they simply passed through and fell victim to the desert's relentless hunger. The hollow itself seems to collect the remains of those who venture too far from water and safety.@@N

