#796
@@yCrumbling Waystone@@N~
@@yAn ancient stone marker of black granite juts from the sand like a broken tooth, its surface covered in worn glyphs that spiral from base to top. The monument stands at a crossroads of sorts, with dunes sloping away in all directions, suggesting this was once an important landmark for travelers. The carvings suggest three cardinal directions, though the weathering makes it difficult to determine which is which. Time and millennia of wind-driven sand have nearly erased whatever message it once conveyed, though you can still make out fragments of words in a script that predates any modern language. Deep scratches and pitting mark the stone where countless travelers once touched it, leaving marks of their passage. The base of the waystone is surrounded by a depression worn into the sand by the feet of thousands of pilgrims, merchants, and adventurers who paused here seeking guidance. Small offerings—coins, tokens, fragments of cloth—have been left by countless visitors over the centuries, though time has rendered most unidentifiable.@@N

