#801
@@yVulture Circle@@N~
@@yCircling above in an endless and hypnotic pattern, a dozen or more vultures ride the thermals of rising hot air with mechanical precision and absolute certainty. Their shadows cross the cracked earth in patterns as old as death itself, ancient, inevitable, and utterly impersonal. The birds seem to have been circling this same place forever, waiting with infinite patience for the next meal. Occasionally one descends, wings folded close to its powerful body, dropping rapidly through the air toward some prey, real or imagined. But they always return to their sky-paths, never landing for long, never allowing themselves the comfort of rest. The sight is simultaneously natural and profoundly unsettling—these are nature's undertakers, organized and patient. The constant circling creates an almost hypnotic and dizzying effect, as if you're watching the very clockwork of death itself turning in the sky above. The knowledge that they're waiting for you to weaken is inescapable.@@N

