#802
@@ySand Pit@@N~
@@yA large depression in the dunes forms a natural pit, its sides steep and alarmingly unstable. The walls shift and slide when touched, threatening to collapse inward with the slightest provocation. The pit extends downward perhaps twenty feet or more, creating a dangerous funnel that seems to draw your eye ever deeper. At the bottom, the sand appears noticeably darker and more compact than the surrounding dunes, compressed and hardened by ages of weight and pressure. Strange markings crisscross the pit's floor—perhaps the recent passage of large creatures, or perhaps evidence of ancient excavations and digging by those seeking whatever lies below. The pit feels alive somehow, possessed of a watchful quality, as if something beneath the surface is waiting and watching, anticipating the precise moment when you lose your footing and descend into its hungry depths. The air rising from the pit seems slightly cooler, hinting at deeper chambers or caves below.@@N

