#804
@@yWind-Carved Canyon Mouth@@N~
@@yA canyon entrance has been carved by millennia of relentless wind erosion and rare but violent water flows. The walls stand like the massive jaws of some colossal sleeping beast, each face of stone towering hundreds of feet overhead. Deep shadows cast by the stone walls create an almost tangible darkness across the canyon floor, a welcome relief from the merciless sun above. The stone itself tells stories of ages past—layered sediments in shades of rust, gold, and deep crimson create natural striations that speak of geological epochs. Weathered stone formations and natural sculptures suggest this was once a vital trade route, a crucial artery through the desert where merchants moved their caravans laden with goods. The canyon walls show clear evidence of water wear—smooth channels and rounded boulders bear testimony to flash floods in the distant past. The canyon mouth itself is the width of a small city block, narrowing as you venture deeper into shadow.@@N

