#806
@@yAncient Road Fragment@@N~
@@yRemnants of an old stone road push persistently through the sand despite millennia of burial and erosion. The paving stones are massive and fitted together with extraordinary precision that speaks eloquently of a civilization now lost to time. Each stone is cut from black granite and marble, fitted so tightly that a blade cannot pass between them. The scale of the construction is impressive—each individual stone weighs many tons, yet they remain aligned and level after ages of exposure to the desert's harshness. The path leads toward distant ruins visible in the heat-shimmer to the south, rising gradually from the sand as if climbing toward the sky. Alongside the road, the faint outline of what once were pillars or markers suggests a grand processional way. Carved into some of the visible stones are decorative grooves and patterns—geometric designs and occasional pictographs depicting scenes of triumph and civilization. This was once a route of prestige and power.@@N

